issue.title: UI rjsf alternative

labels.name: Spike
labels.description: A small chunk of work with the objective of gathering information.

issue.body:
# Spike

rjsf is not very intuitive to use and has some complexity.
We don't even use a quarter of the lib options.

## Objective
Find an alternative solution to the rjsf lib.
The target is to reduce the complexity.
We may also decide to implement one that will fit our purposes.

## Scope
1-1.5 days

## Output
Pros and cons of each lib/approach

comment.body: Additional complexity is in plugin display component (`PluginSelectorTemplate`). It's coupled to global config through `PLUGIN_SCHEMA_PATH`. I think this stems from the fact that our state management in tabs is done poorly.

issue.title: Remove link-local addresses from Island UI

labels.name: Bug
labels.description: An error, flaw, misbehavior or failure in the Monkey or Monkey Island.

issue.body:
<!--
Thank you for reporting a bug to make Infection Monkey better.

Please fill in as much of the template below as you're able.
-->

## Describe the bug

Link local addresses are non-routable, but they get added to the island IP's. There's no point for agents to try and call these IP's and Island UI shouldn't display them.

## To Reproduce
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Configure link-local IP
2. Run the island
3. Link local IP is displayed for accessing the UI

## Expected behavior
Shouldn't show link-local IP's

# Tasks

- [ ] Change `common.network.network_utils.get_network_interfaces` to filter out link-local addresses

issue.title: Packer leaves powershell remoting enabled

labels.name: Feature
labels.description: Issue that describes a new feature to be implemented.

issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Packer runs WINRM and uses powershell remoting ports to do its job. This means that we need to find workarounds to block powershell remoting with GCP firewall rules, but packer images should be independent of cloud environment.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
[Use a cleanup script to disable PowerShell remoting.](https://hodgkins.io/best-practices-with-packer-and-windows#disable-winrm-on-build-completion-and-only-enable-it-on-first-boot)

comment.body: Similarly, RDP is also enabled on most if not all Windows machines. That means most if not all of them are exploitable via RDP. We could probably disable RDP on a per-user basis, so that it is closed to the accounts used in EtE tests, but open to developer accounts

issue.title: Upgrade to Node.js 20
issue.body:
## Description

Node.js 16 is EOL as of 2023-09-11. Upgrade to Node.js 20 (latest version).

## Side efficts

Node.js 20 is not available on Ubuntu Bionic 18.04. We must upgrade our build system to Ubuntu Jammy 22.04 or Focal 20.04. This means that the Island AppImage may not be runable on certain other distributions. Use distrowatch.com to compare glibc versions and make a decision about which Ubuntu we should upgrade to.

In addition, the base container for our Island Docker image may need to be upgraded.

## Note

The current method of installing Node.js in the Linux deployment script is deprecated.
![image](https://github.com/guardicore/monkey/assets/19957806/ec70457f-68dd-427f-987d-9d2e6f5a7da0)

## Tasks

- [x] Choose a new version of Ubuntu for our build system
  - Ubuntu 20.04 is the minimum version supporting glibc 2.28+
  - All our previous supported OSs for Island should still work, with the exception of Ubuntu 18.04
- [x] Take a snapshot of the build instance
- [x] Upgrade the build instance to 20.04+
- [x] Upgrade node.js to v20
    - [x] Fix deployment scripts and get this running from source
    - [x] Upgrade node.js to v20 on the Windows build node
    - [x] Upgrade the linux island instances
    - [x] Test and fix the Docker build
    - [x] Test and fix the AppImage build
    - [x] Test and fix the MSI build
